<date>1572314727148</date><Rate>5</Rate>< text>
My dentist of 20 years retired and my husband and I were referred to Surfside Dental.  This dental office and team are perfection!  Kelly, the office manager, couldn't be more pleasant & professional and Dr. McMahan is very friendly, kind, and empathetic to each dental situation.  He doesn't "push" his business or treatment onto patients like I have experienced at other dental offices. Surfside  Dental is  beautifully remodeled  which includes the most updated dental technology.

I used  to never want dental x-rays because of radiation exposure, but their x-ray equipment produces very minimal radiation.  Each time I walk into Surfside Dental I feel very calm and relaxed.  While in a dental chair I love being mesmerized by watching the  (large flatscreen TV) beach front webcams and listening to the calming music.  The entire Surfside Dental experience  could not be more pleasant! We are extremely thankful to have Dr. McMahan and his team providing our dental care! Another plus is parking. Parking is very easily assessable.<//text>

< review>
To be completely honest, I don't know why this place gets such a low rating both on Yelp and Google. It seems like a really popular spot, and everyone was going here, and not the next two spots. Now, as a Canadian I don't fully know what average price for breakfast food is, but since it is an airport, I will say that it is fairly reasonable. I ordered an omelette with sausage inside, with sides of toast, salsa, tater tots, and avocado. And with sour cream as dipping. Again, as a Canadian, I found the portions to be huge, and the price isn't bad(under 15 dollars). The service was nice, too. The lady at the counter walked us through the menu. The food was really good too, and they cook many things fresh.< /review>

<user_name>Roy Pitts< /user_name><Rate>4<//Rate><pics>None</pics>< Resp>
None< /Resp>
<Review>This is my main boat launch as I live nearby. There are two ramps. The north ramp is a little silted in. The kayaks and skiffs use this one. The south ramp is good for most shallow draft boats if you have a one foot plus tide at The Blakes Landing tide station. If your bringing your big Gradey White wait for plus two. It's a Marin County launch ramp. There are clean flush toilets and it's five bucks to launch and park. Over night parking is allowed if you are boat camping on the west side of the bay. The lower paved lot fills up pretty quick in the early morning. but there is a dirt lot up the hill for overflow. It's Grand Central Station when the bite is on and the kayak tours are running. There are always parking spots after Eleven a.m. No fuel but you can get some really excellent pricy food at Nick Cove. See you on the water.<//Review>< user>
101429412899211346410< /user>
<gmapID>0x8085d2eb4dd9e3ed:0x3b653cafc05ac36a</gmapID>< date>

<Rating>5<//Rating><text>This is the main location were I launch my boat to fish Tomales Bay for Halibut. The mouth of the bay is great for Salmon when Salmon are running. For Halibut go to the back of the bay in about 12ft of water this is were I spearfish for California Halibut. I've bagged nice fish every time that I dive there.Visibility can be 20ft on a great day too zero on a heavy tide. A sandy rolling bottom is what you encounter. Expect Thresher Sharks , Leopard Sharks and Sting Rays. Not for beginners!< /text><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNdxVla3ehSBpnpEmtN1FvvtYM0Djepgo3N-Bx4=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNe1k4oHswPc47O5GdC-fnElNAX68nUqtCKHlmW=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures><Response>None</Response>< Gmap_id>

< Rate>
5</Rate>
< text>
My family and I have been coming to this restaurant for nearly 20 years, with my parents, and their families, when they were in their former location down the street by Cal Mart. This is our favorite Mexican restaurant, and we are so excited that they have reopened. This place has the same great food and good service that we were accustomed to in their other location. While the room arrangement isn't as comfortable and cozy as their former location, come to enjoy the food.  Over the years, our family has sampled many dishes. Here are our favorites: the enchiladas or burrito, with sour cream, guacamole, creamy red sauce and juicy shredded chicken; the fajitas with perfectly sauteed red and green bell peppers; the tacos or tostada with fresh lettuce, tomato, and your choice of meat; the spicy camarones a la diabla that generous portion of succulent shrimp will not disappoint); or on the lighter side, have a perfectly cooked quesadilla or chile relleno. The beans and rice on the side are also worth a mention because they have a great texture and flavor, best I've had yet.< /text>

Robin Wong<//Name>
<time>1618805495158< /time><Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
Like many others, I started biking more frequently during the pandemic, and it was great exercise! After I got my new Specialized Roubaix, my left knee started to feel some pains at the end of my longer rides (paradise loop, King's mountain, etc). I tried adjusting the seat/cleats on my own with the help of YouTube, but the pain only lessened slightly and shifted to other parts of my knee. My friends recommended Pedro, and I was hesitant due to the cost, but I'm glad I signed up!

The office is in a nice location in the Marina, and Pedro was welcoming and super easy to talk to. He looked at my cleats and asked who installed them *smirked and said I did*. I then sat on my bike while on the Wahoo and pedaled while he made adjustments. Pedro adjusted my handlebars, seat position, and even adjusted the hoods closer to be more in line with my shoulder width. The bike fit was a simple process and I actually wished it lasted more than an hour so I could continue chatting with him. Since the adjustments, I have had ZERO knee pain, absolutely none! According to his data, I was also able to have more efficiency in my riding.

If you're having some pains or feel like your fit is not great, and you're not comfortable adjusting the bike yourself, I highly recommend going to Pedro for a fit. Your body is worth the few hundred dollars to ensure there is no long term injury.</review>

<rating>5< /rating>< Review>
I went to Pedro in SF to get a Peloton fitting, and measurements as I'm planning to buy a road bike soon. He was clearly very experienced and easy to talk to. He aligned my cleats (I had them too far back), helped me find the best seat and handlebar positions (my handlebars were way too high), and what a good posture looks like (I had my hands in the wrong place). Immediately after the session he sent me pictures of all the settings and an email with all of my measurements.

I participated in a 120 "mile" Pelofondo that same weekend over the course of 5.5 hours in one day with no problem (more than twice as long as my previous longest session or highest "mileage"). Today, a week after the fitting, I just set a new 45 min PR basically by accident and I think my FTP is going to see a double digit improvement. I would 100% recommend Pedro to anyone who is serious about riding, and I look forward to seeing him again when I buy a new bike. Even indoors, fit and posture really does make a big difference.</Review>

<Rating>5</Rating>< review>
I have been racing triathlon, specifically olympic distance and IM 70.3 for the past 4-5 years. Always feeling not ideal on my tri bike position after many many tweaks, did an expensive fitting with another shop in SF about 2 years ago, still not helping much. My main struggling are 1) not able to apply glute strength enough; 2) upper body either too straight or too stretch; 3) suffering a lot of quad cramping immediately after T2 for 70.3 races.

A friend of mine introduced me to Pedro earlier this year, I wasn't sure it would help at first but decided to give it a try. Went to the shop for a new fitting (because I want him to have a completely new look into it), it 3 weeks before my first 70.3 races this year, Pedro listened to my above issues to start with, and looked into my position on the trainer and immediately gave a few recommendation. We worked on it step by steps in the next 1.5 hours; every adjustment he made, we either see some immediate improvements on the power output or discuss over the difference on feelings, he took my feedback very well and incorporated into the further steps. After the session I felt pretty happy and confident about the above problems being mostly fixed.

I raced two 70.3 races after the fitting, feeling much better on the tri-position, didn't have cramping problem in the entire run on both occasions. Glad the new fitting is proven in the real world as well. Now i'm looking forward to the next season, very sure it would be even better once i spend majority of the training on the position. I will definitely go back to Pedro for a few follow-up fittings as well.

Also additional note: he didn't upsell unnecessary components to me like some other fitting shops.< /review>

< review>
I've had my Felt IA-16 tri bike for a year.  I did get a pre-purchase fit as well as a fit when I picked the bike up.  It felt pretty good at the time and I really didn't ride it nearly as much as I planned to.
I recently started training to enter into some triathlons so I am starting to ride more and found that it really wasn't as comfortable as I had first thought.
The coach I am working with sent out a notification that Pedro was coming to SoCal for a few days and was taking appointments for fittings.
I set up a time and when I arrived, before I even took the bike out of my car, Pedro looked at me and asked why I was riding it like a road bike.
I was a little surprised he noticed that right off.
Needless to say, Pedro made a few key adjustments and it was amazing how much better it felt.  A couple more tweaks here and there and we were done.
Pedro is very knowledgeable, personable, and all around fun to talk with.
I took the bike for a good 2 hour ride the next day and was so impressed with the new fit.
I was able to stay in the saddle and in aero much longer than I had before and I could breathe.
I would recommend Pedro to anyone for a fitting, whether you think you need it or not.
I will definitely be seeing him again whenever he is in the Los Angeles area.< /review>

<review>The process for the cost from Moving Nation was its saving grace. They did not charge me much more than originally quoted, however, the real issues were in the actual moving/packing and unpacking. As I've been unpacking, I noticed that despite being wrapped in bubble wrap, a number of my pots and pans had deep scratches on them, which at least they weren't on the inside of the pan where you actually cook, but still diminishes the quality of the cookware. They also put our Ikea bedframe back together wrong, so in the middle of the night one evening, we heard a loud noise, and then looked the next day and saw that the metal bar sections had not been properly screwed in, so we ended up having to reconstruct it properly. We also notice quote a bit of damage on that, despite the frame being only a couple years old. They also asked to throw away a bunch of plastic packing wrap, to which I thought they would throw it in the trash can, but instead, they put it in recycling, which is wrong. Lastly, there was a bit of a language barrier. I know moving is hard work, and I wasn't standing over them watching every move as they originally packed our furniture, so when they delivered it, they wheeled it in asking me where to put some of it, and I didn't know what it was, to which they got frustrated with me. The language barrier definitely made that part worse. I get that these guys are stressed, (they under-calculated how far our city was from another job in a different city, and seemed to be rushing to complete our job so they could make it back to the other one), but clearer communication, and better common sense would have helped this. Would I use them again? Probably not. <text>TLDR: Do not book with this company! Unprofessional, uncommunicative, and almost a month late.

We booked a move for 10/23 and The sales rep that I initially spoke with told me that our order would be delivered between 11/3 and 11/9. He then walked through the contract with me over the phone while I digitally signed it. During that section he said ‚Äúthis is what we discussed‚Äù. I understand it is on me to have read the contract more thoroughly but I feel it was very deceptive. The actual timeline was 17 business days from our first available date, which would be 11/24.

We got a call a day before they were supposed to be there and were told that they would be coming on our backup day, a day later than expected. Our things left our San Francisco apartment on 10/24. When they movers were in our apartment they were very unprofessional. The leader repeatedly took his mask off even when I asked him to keep it on at all times (locally it is required to keep masks on indoors and outdoors). When disassembling our furniture for packing, one of the movers did not know what a screwdriver was (picked up a socket wrench and asked me if that was a screwdriver). We also found several screws and washers on the floor after they had packed and left, so we had to save the hardware pieces for our bed.

Over the month of November we called frequently but were not able to get updates. We were told that our things left the California warehouse on 11/23, the day before the end of our delivery window for a cross country move, so clearly they had no intention of making the deadline. It was then delayed again indefinitely due to mechanical issues and we couldn‚Äôt get a callback or any information regarding our timeline.

We had given up on seeing our possessions again by December and had started to look into possible legal action.

We finally received our things on 12/19, nearly 2 months after it left.

We were given a refund of $30/business day over the window, but this was a very small refund. Very upset because we were missing our possessions 7 days a week, not just week days, and $30/day is not enough to make up for the lost time.

When our things did arrive we were not missing anything, only one item was slightly damaged and the movers on the move-in end were very professional and courteous, but this is the only good thing I can say about the company.</text>< Pics>

< Text>
Hello dear reader, I pray listen well ‚Äì
and bear ye witness to my tale of woe;
of movers whose help was a living hell,
and for whom there is no rating too low.

My ask was simply to just use one truck,
and to this one request they did agree.
But once cash changed hands, I was out of luck;
instead of one truck, they would now use three.

I wish this lie would also be the last,
But beyond lying, they also weren‚Äôt fast.

I called to complain, three trucks would not do.
‚ÄúToo bad,‚Äù they said, ‚Äúyou signed and you agreed.‚Äù
What their salesman said mattered not, I knew,
Phone conversations leave nothing to read.

Lo, they did say they recorded all calls!
So I bid them play our conversation,
And hoped they did not have me by the balls.
But, alas, I found more consternation.

The files, it seemed, were all there - except one.
‚ÄúIt‚Äôs unplayable,‚Äù claimed Moving Nation.

Three hours we spent, arguing on the phone;
But customer service refused our pleas.
‚ÄúWe‚Äôve got you now,‚Äù said the rep‚Äôs icy tone,
‚ÄúYou‚Äôve no choice but to pay our surprise fees.‚Äù

At this point despair started to begin.
With less than seven days until the move,
Our contract made it clear - we were locked in.
We told ourselves things can only improve.

Unfortunately, this was just the start.
There‚Äôs worse yet to come, but that‚Äôs the next part.

At least the movers came on the right date,
Though they did give a two hour time line,
And arrived forty and five minutes late.
They packed our things, and again made us sign.

We should have known, by this point in the tale,
To expect trickery to be in play,
They used fine print to change the terms of sale,
And increased costs which we then had to pay.

‚ÄúThe worst‚Äôs done,‚Äù we thought, but we were na√Øve.
Now they had our stuff. There‚Äôd be no reprieve.

Moved into our new place, yet without stuff.
We called about our delivery date.
As you expect, the news we got was rough.
Our things may come up to thirty days late!

Ten days, contract said - thirty's too delayed!
But no, the fine print snuck something in deep.
Their receipt stated, beyond that we paid,
‚ÄúONE MONTH ‚Äòfore we‚Äôd have our bed back to sleep.‚Äù

Cared not what they said during their sales pitch
It‚Äôs just their M.O. to bait and then switch.

Disney was planned, but they cared not for me.
Asked if they expected us to postpone,
They said, ‚ÄúHope not,‚Äù but gave no guarantee.
They told me that one reaps what they have sewn.

A month passed us, without our clothes or bed.
Phone calls showed they did not know when they‚Äôd come.
By now our hope for good service was dead.
Completely at their mercy, we were glum.

Fearing that they might want to punish us,
We grew meek, and did not  put up a fuss.

Finally, our delivery day came.
It arrived over three hours late, mind you -
but of course they did not accept the blame
At least no shuttle was needed; that‚Äôs true.

Our fragile boxes all came rather squished.
Our bed and chairs were, of course, broken too.
They told us to report it if we wished.
WE would report it, to them and to you.

So noble reader, we draw near the end,
But don‚Äôt leave ‚Äòfore I tell you of my friend.

This tale does not end with me and my things,
It‚Äôs not just me that was duped by these crooks.
They lost my wife‚Äôs crafting box and some strings,
And gave us someone else‚Äôs photo books.

Some wedding pictures, and a child‚Äôs first steps,
All of this left with us without a thought.
We found names and called the company reps,
We knew the owners must be quite distraught.

Moving Nation did nothing; one more fail.
We found the owners, and sent it by mail.

And so it ends, this moving tale of woe,
With every moving fear all come true,
My things broken and lost; my spirits low,
Few recourse options, but I could review!

Please heed my warning, whoever you are,
Do not listen to their saccharin lies
For the worst; Moving Nation sets the bar.
It was so bad, I hope their business dies.

I have nothing more to say or to tell.
Moving Nation, you can go straight to hell!</Text>

<review>My wife and I purchased a home in Marietta Georgia on September 2, 2020. Upon the purchase we started to research long distance moving companies. Having interviewed five companies we narrowed it down to two eventually going with Moving Nation. Having had a very good experience with their representative Eric Meyer the price of $10443.27 was agreed upon and the contract signed. The pick up date was to be October 1, 2020. Once the contract was signed and the down payment of $2341.00 was paid we were passed onto Lisa for finalizing everything. She as Eric and Jimmy another sales rep seemed very pleasant.

Well moving day came and the two trucks with four men showed up being very courteous and professional. We had packed most of our belongings ourselves, leaving the big items. I watch over them very closely and they were being very careful packing everything properly as we had gone through this a year and a half ago because of the Woosley fire. All seemed to be going smoothly.

Then at around 4pm things seemed to come to a halt. All the big pieces which had been packed and ready to be put on the truck were standing in the house as the head man made phone calls. Well low and behold he came to us and said that unless we paid them another $5242.00 they were finished loading the trucks. But you have eighty percent of our furnishings on your truck. We have been told by our supervisor we are done unless you pay. I asked to speak with the supervisor only to be told I wasn't allowed to. So we called Eric and Lisa only to be transfered to an answering machine. At this time what do you do, we paid, they finished and left with our gear having been told by Eric and Jimmy that on October 2, 2020 our furnishings will be transferred onto a bigger truck and leave for Georgia ariving 7 to 10 days later.
As Monday October 12th approached I called to get an update as to when we were to recieve our belongings only to find out that everything was in storage in Sacramento. Are you kidding me pick the gear up in Malibu and drive it to Sacramento to transfer to another truck, not very efficent. We have actually been told our belonging have been loaded on three different occasions only to find out it wasn't true. First time Nadine said it will load on Thursday October 15th and leave on  Friday October 16. Didn't happen we have now been passed onto Tina who twice has said we will load this weekend and travel out begining of week. Everytime I call for update it gets pushed for another week or two.
November 11, 2020 sitting in an empty house in Georgia with two chairs a blow up bed, dog, and cat. Furshings still in sacramento with no firm date as to when we will if ever see our lovely belongings. The stress that has been perpetrated upon my wife and I is palpable.

Would anyone be interested in putting together a class action law suite?

We finally mailed in our list of damaged and lost items to the home office. Sent signed registered receipt to be returned thus so we would know it was received. Came back signed covid 19. Spoke with Tina about this she did confirm that it was in there mail box and said the post man signed it that way.  YET ANOTHER LIE!!!!

< Review>
DO NOT HIRE THIS COMPANY!  They will give you a low estimate while telling you that they overestimate so that there will be no additional charges at delivery.  They talk a great game about their service- there are none.  They call before the move after the time in which you can cancel and then up the cost.  They do not contact you at all about when they are coming- in fact communication is nil and they never return calls.  If you do manage to get an answer- you get Lisa who is arrogant and condescending with no customer service skills.  When they show up- suddenly the cost doubles due to more cubic feet.  They also don‚Äôt tell you that they take your stuff to their warehouse and load it into a storage unit.  Why not load truck and drive it to me then?  The inventory papers were unreadable and driver couldn‚Äôt give me a receipt for my paper but promised to email to me right away.  Still waiting.....Then the waiting game begins.... they don‚Äôt contact you- you have to make repeated calls but dispatcher can‚Äôt give you an answer.  Then finally they tell you that truck is loaded and delivery will be the next day or day after.  They do not show up of course.  They tell me they just finished a job a few hours north but for some reason can‚Äôt get therefor another 8 hrs.  Truth is that my stuff was sitting somewhere an hour south of me- probably in another storage unit.  The driver was a contract driver who was very nice but unaware of what Type of items I had which tells me he did not oversee packing of truck.  He arrived in an enterprise rental truck and someone following him that they had called that day to help- also very nice but had never done moving before.  My boxes and totes arrived torn and smashed. Things that had been packed in boxes prior were carried in individually.  Who knows what is sitting on storage area floor that never made it.  Dish and glass boxes were upside down as were most boxes marked fragile.  I would not give them any stars if I was able.  Believe that any positive reviews are probably friends and family as there are a lot of other people who suffered the same nightmare experience that I did. As an addendum- after unpacking my belongings- we discovered that so much weight had been piled our recliner that the springs and metal pieces holding seat had snapped and we had to throw it out as well as a lot of dented and broken items.  Never found my silverware and some dishes.  All of my wood furniture pieces were scratched and wood finish worn away despite being covered!!!</Review>

<username>Matthew Reese</username>< review>
Unprofessional Moving Company
I used Moving Nation for a cross country move as I was sold a move by Joe Campbell. My move was difficult in that the house at origin was three stories. I explained all of the nuances to Joe in detail as everything seemed to be properly explained, cost determined, dates determined (1 day of packing and one day of loading for a 4 bedroom place).

However, after I submitted my deposit, everything changed.
I found out that none of the details had been passed to the operations personnel. Instead of the two day move, the movers showed up at 1:30 on the second day having already worked a move that morning.

I was told by the foreman that "where were we supposed to find a crew to conduct a two day packing job in mid-summer."

I was also told that that some of the movers, "had apparently either embellished their experience levels as they were pressed to find personnel to work the move"

One mover actually slammed an article of mine down on my hardwood floor because he was reprimanded by his supervisor for improperly moving the article, in which he damaged it by breaking the side tray from improperly carrying it.

I was taken aback, as this was supposed to be a professional moving company, as it was their responsibility to find adequate trained personnel for a move.

In addition to being  unprofessional, inexperienced, breaking items and damaging my house in the process., the packing was woefully subpar. The the boxes were not properly labeled, they did not even have the room of origin labeled on them, as I was told that this was company policy.

I have never had rooms of origin not written on the boxes (i.e. Master bedroom, guest room etc.)

The move foreman was inexperienced and failed to properly monitor the process. The movers were also unsafe as several items were improperly moved almost resulting in injuries to the movers due to their lack of experience.

At destination, several items were broken due to their rushed packing job. I would also like to mention that there were lose items due to the rushed job, as several items were missed, and had to be either packed last minute or stashed in boxes with items from other parts of the house.

For these reasons, i must give them 1 star and recommend not using this company.</review>

<Pics>None</Pics>< Text>
I usually don't review health providers, but this dental office was too unique not to talk about.

I needed cleaning and filling, and as every time I go to a dentist, I was nervous about the pain.

From the minute I entered the place, I felt it was quite different from other offices I have been to. It feels like you are in a high end spa... Very nice decor, colors and feel. They even have birds and nature sounds in the background, and their chairs have massage features... It really feels relaxing!

I was impressed with the doctor's bedside manners. Very good listener, and patient in explaining what went wrong with my teeth and the treatment he would use for that. He even pointed out my most economical options (very rare to find in a dentist!!). Don't be shy to ask if they can give you a payment plan.

During the procedure, the doctor paused from time to time to ask me how I was feeling and encouraged me to tell him if I had any concern or feel any pain. I really like that personal care and attention, versus feeling I'm on a conveyor belt, and rushed out the door (I'm sure a lot of people can relate to that lol ).

Overall, it was a great experience, with great people. I would recommend them to anyone!</Text>

<user_name>Sharon Powers<//user_name><Date>1547968663097<//Date><rate>4<//rate>< text>
I took my grand kids for dinner to Chuck E cheese's. This place is made for children to have fun, and the kids did have fun. While it was my 1st experience here, the children had been here many times before with their parents. The pizza is only  so, so, but the salad bar is fairly decent. Besides pizza, we also ordered a side of  celery, wings, bread sticks, and cheesy bread, with all the dips-- The girls demolished the breadsticks, and I loved the cheesy bread and wings. We all had salad which was very good.
The girls played for something called tickets which we turned in for prizes.  The place is chaotic, wild, and entirely fun for little ones.   I can't imagine a more fun place for little ones. As a grandparent, though, I had to keep my eyes alert at all times to watch out for my 2 little grand girls.</text>

<time>1537971377681<//time><Rating>4<//Rating>< review>
All the kids in the place seemed to be having a great time. The games are geared toward children. Although the adults all seemed to enjoy them as well. The staff was helpful and friendly. They give you enough room at the table for a large group. Chuck E Cheese comes out once for all of the kids having a party during that time and is out for about 10 minutes or so. Not a fan of the pizza. But the wings weren't bad. The party packages seemed reasonably priced. There was a sign saying on Sundays they have a sensory block for a couple hours, where anyone who is negatively affected by the bright lights and noises can come and enjoy a less bright and noisy atmosphere.< /review>

<user_name>Tania Guillen<//user_name>< review>
I am so upset. I called rose hills the first week of Mother Day and I asked them when I should remove the stuff from my moms gravesite. The lady I spoke to advised me that on the 20th all things had to be picked up. I asked her more than one time and she assured me that the pick up date was on the 20th. To my surpirse, I went yesterday to go pick up my moms stuff and they threw everything away. I started crying because I bought my mom so many cute things to decorate for Mothers Day. This shouldve not happened and it did because the lady on the phone gave me wrong information. It was about 300 dollars worth of stuff. Everything was brand new and I am so disappointed because I previously had given 5 stars.<//review>

I greatly appreciate that I was able to temporarily entomb my father during the pandemic.  I don't know of any other mortuary that offered this option.  If you are asking me to rate the service at Rose Hills before my father's funeral I'd say a 1 star, but if you are asking me to rate the service the day of the funeral I would say 5 stars.  My father died in April, but was not buried (by choice) in November.  I spoke to at least 3 people the week after he died and they all had something different to say.  The right hand wasn't talking to the left hand.  There was so much confusion that I asked to speak with a supervisor.  When my coordinator called the following week I spent about 1.5hrs on the phone.  We went over all the details regarding my father's service and the options I had due to the pandemic.  When I was ready to plan his funeral, it was impossible to make any plans.  I sent emails, left voicemails and it would take up to 4 days to get a response.  Even a week before the funeral I could not get an answer to my questions.  I spoke to her 3 times during the planning, but it was in between clients so our conversations were very brief.  I spoke to her 1 week before my father's funeral and never spoke to her again. < text>
My mother passed away on 3/13/2020.  The family has 6 plots purchased many years ago.  When my father passed away 30 years ago, she purchased an individual marker for herself.  When I went to make arrangements for my mother, they had no record of her purchase.  Fortunately, I found the receipt, along with a letter from Rose Hills stating that it was made and where it was stored; however, the ORIGINAL MARKER WAS LOST.  They said they would provide a new one.  Months later they installed a new marker, but it had an INCORRECT INSCRIPTION.  Months after this, I was told a correct one had been installed.  But again, another lie.  I went to visit and the incorrect marker was still there.  We couldn't have a burial or funeral for my mother, because of the pandemic, which is understandable, but 8 MONTHS LATER AND THIS IS STILL NOT RESOVED.  I ADVISE EVERYONE "DO NOT" PURCHASE ANYTHING IN ADVANCE.   Not only do I think it's unsympathetic and rude to ask grieving customers, while they are making arrangements for their loved ones, to plan their own demise, it's unwise.  Seems to be a ploy to get your money in advance knowing that the records might be lost and re-purchased unknowingly when the person actual dies.
Overall this has been a  stressful ordeal.  I CONTINUOSLY HAVE TO FOLLOW-UP.  There were also delays with the death certificates and miscommunication on other issues.   I wish our family plots were located at smaller local cemetery.  They seem to have more empathy and understanding towards the families needs. And they keep up the landscaping maintenance.  Whenever I visit, I need to have clippers and tools with me.  Also, I need to remember the flower removal day because they will throw out brand new flowers...doesn't matter if it's their birthday, etc.
I also know others who have and still are experiencing negative ordeals with Rose Hills.  I truly believe Rose Hills is more focused on financial gain then focus on the concerns of their clients!</text>

< Text>
As a prearranged customer of Rosehills, with prior great service received, it is very unfortunate to leave 3 stars as a review, especially during this pandemic and the challenges we all face. However, the need to let people know first hand, our recent experience, is the right thing to do. We do understand a delay in laying our loved one to rest, especially during this globally impacted time. It took over three weeks to lay our mother to rest due to scheduling issues on Rosehills‚Äô end. Meanwhile, other mortuaries and memorial parks were more efficient and timely in rendering their internment services.

Our prearranged services obviously had to be modified to comply with covid protocol. Yet, the encumbered fees were fully charged, without any refunds for services not utilized. On the day of the service all was going smoothly as we hoped, except for another oversight on the part of Rosehills. It is a small oversight, but lends to the lack of attention our family expected or received. The memorial cards we ordered were not given to us to distribute to our family and friends. When we brought this up with the representative, he told us we didn‚Äôt pay for any cards and proceeded to show us a printout of what was included. I kindly asked to have someone contact me as I didn‚Äôt want to draw any more attention than he‚Äôd already done.

After the burial, when most had already left, this gentleman realized his mistake, and told us the cards were still at his office. Thankfully, we received the cards, but the run of the mill treatment we received from the beginning of this experience, until the end, left more disheartened feelings. There was no guidance from any Rosehills staff members, including our long time sales representative. What we took away from this was much disappointment and a need to alert others. We plan to move the remaining prearranged services we have away from Rosehills along with the several other properties we own there.< /Text>

<Name>andrew kim< /Name>< Review>
It is painful to even give one STAR to Rose Hills Memorial Park.  My beloved mother recently passed away and because she care so much for us and did not want to burden us with the monument expense, she financed in advance since 2009 and paid in full.  She worked at a Dry Cleaner and made every single payment for the monument with an interest rate of 9.9% given by RH Cemetery Corp (I guess Rose Hills is in the Finance business as well).

Since the death of my mother, I have been trying to place the order for the Monument she paid with her hard earn money.  However, Rose Hills Interment Office Department for whatever reason does not want to place the order.  I have either spoken or directed to 4 different Associates (Austin, Michael, Lauren, can't remember the 4th person name) who promise me they will call me back to place the order, but never received one single call back from any of the Associates.  Therefore, I decided to speak with the Manager, Joshua Ramirez.  We had a conversation and once again, I was promised by Joshua that my mother's case will be a priority on his list and he will PERSONALLY look into it and CALL ME BACK within 24 hours with an update.  And guess what??!!!  He NEVER call me back either. I guess management at Rose Hills train the Associates to NEVER call back your customers.

So, I decided to speak with someone above Joshua Ramirez.  I was told that his name is Scott Mitchell.  I called Scott Mitchell extension, but of course no answers and no way to leave a voicemail. The phone keeps ringing, but no answer nor it is setup for voicemail, very convenient.  Basically, I am left with nobody to talk to.

Finally, I decided to cancel the contract and ask for a full refund so we can place the Monument with a different company.  So, I call back to the interment office and told them I want to cancel the contract and request for a full refund.  I spoke with Nichole who transfer me to Jessica in the Business Office who will be handling the refund.  And guess what, the Business Office told me that they could offer a partial refund because the contract was too OLD (Like we all can predict when we are going to die.  If this is the case, then they should not pre-sale funeral arrangements), and for the full refund I need to speak with the Interment Office.  Basically, I am being shuffle from one department to another until I get tired of the situation and finally give up or accept a partial refund.  This is the perfect SCAM not to deliver on the service already paid since 2009 or send you away with a fraction of the hard earn money my mother paid for. I can't believe that Rose Hills has the nerve to offer only partial refund when in fact, the $7500 my mother paid back in 2009, today, it will be worth much more.  Rose Hills was holding onto my mother's money earning interest and now, they only want to give a portion of that money.  Please tell me that this isn't right.

I am going to fight this until the end of it for my mother's hard earned cash.  Rose Hills is taking advantage of my poor mother in her grave and it is not fair.  Rose Hills should be ashamed of their business practices of pre-selling funeral arrangements and not delivering on their promises or telling you that you will only get partial refund because the contract is too OLD.  Please, do not pre-purchase anything from Rose Hills.  Otherwise, you will suffer the same pain I am going thru right now.  I hope my long review will prevent many of you out there making funeral arrangements for your love ones at Rose Hills.

Regards,
Andrew Kim< /Review>

<Review>Drove 3,000 miles to visit my grandfather's grave for the first time. Was met with insensitive security guards blocking the access road to the grounds due to COVID-19. And they couldn't care less about my long journey.

Since it wasn't safe for me to visit the living, I chose to go visit my ancestors and family members who had passed away with the ultimate goal of seeing my paternal grandfather's grave for the first time. He died when I was too little to know him.

Every other graveyard in the nation that I passed through had closed their offices and buildings for obvious reasons (to protect their workers) and in compliance with local ordinances. But none of them closed their grounds out of respect for those who wanted to visit the testing places of their family members. This put NO ONE at risk, and gave me NO REASON to think or suspect that rose hills would turn me away since I didn't encounter any other cemeteries that were closed.

And yet Rose Hills chose to post security guards at their access roads. Closing the GROUNDS is despicable. You cannot keep people from visiting their FAMILY members resting in a place the FAMILY paid for. Your governor's order only required that you close your buildings, not the entire property.

We can not infect the dead with COVID. The only thing putting those security officers at risk was the fact that they were posted there. This was an INSENSITIVE AND UNCALLED FOR move by the cemetery owners. It's one thing to close your gift shop and offices to protect workers but to close the grounds was a slap in the face to me after I finally had the time/opportunity to visit my grandfather's grave. I'm still in disbelief that I was turned away and that an exception was not made given how long I traveled and how many days I slept in my car to keep myself and others safe in order to get there. < Review>
This was written on behalf of my mother and our family.   This was our first time planning a memorial service and it was the worst experience.  The initial pick up was very respective, the 2 gentlemen that came to the house to pick up my father's body was very nice, compassionate and gentle.  The 2nd meeting was with Jenny Munoz, arrangement counselor.  She was very professional and went over the package my parents had previously paid for, but honestly, I wish she would have told us one hour is not enough, and having one hour in between services is a horrible idea.  We did not have any more communications with Rose Hills until the day of the service.  We were told to come 30 minutes prior to the service, and that was not enough time.   Our flowers were delivered but not in the chapel, to later find out all 3 arrangements were sitting in some other holding area, so thankfully they were found and delivered to the chapel in time for the service.   The family should have met with the funeral director and technology person prior to the service for the order and especially if it's done in a different language, as the musician did not understand when to play what song.   Then when an unexpected guest went up to speak for an additional 10 minutes, it threw our time line and as the last speaker of the service, I found it VERY disrespectful that your staff were already taking things down in the reception area making all sorts of loud noise.  Our family and guests were rushed out of the chapel so you can prepare for the next service, and as we were half way out of the chapel, I turned around and the next person's coffin was already on the stage.   This was extremely unprofessional and I would NEVER recommend your company to anyone!<//Review>

< review>
Beautiful landscaping and easy to get to. Have 2 loved ones buried here. The viewing room and seating was clean,  plenty of room for guests,  nice koi pond with soothing waterfall outside for those who need a some fresh air during services.  Aside from a few sales reps that could benefit from a training class on etiquette in working with grieving family the selection of services were acceptable. During the funeral they had a long wait to get more dirt to fill the hole to bury the cremated remains which was awkward yet the gentleman overseeing the process was professional, sympathetic and polite.<//review>

<Review>Where do I begin? I was referred to Diane Brooks by a friend and I have to say she was truly a gift from God! Initially we were introduced to discuss the option of preplanning and like most I was hesitant and reluctant to think about or talk about death. However, I am very happy and lucky that I decided to go through with preplanning memorial services and purchasing a burial plot.

When I met Diane she took her time to answer every question that I had even the ones I may have asked several times. She was patient compassionate and truly has a great love for what she does. She throughly walked me through the process from beginning to end! Shortly after purchasing, my mother passed away and I realized how great of a decision I had made. Everything went just ask Diane said it would and she was kind enough to follow up with us through every step of the process to ensure that things went smoothly.

As uncomfortable as it may seem or sound  I recommend everyone consider preplanning. Not only does it take a load off your entire family, it will also allow you to make decisions and choose all memorial or burials options upfront. I was an emotional wreck after losing my mother and having everything already picked out before her passing allowed me to grieve her as peacefully as possible, given the circumstances, without having to make tough decision at the time of her death. Truly the best decision I could have ever made!

I am a firm believer in God and I can't thank him enough for bringing Ms. Diane into my life at such a critical time. I pray that he blesses her for being such a blessing to my entire family. Not only was she amazing, but so were each of her colleagues at Rose Hills who made an unpleasant situation such as death, as pleasant as possible with their caring and compassionate demeanor.

Thank you to everyone that I encountered at Rose Hills!

Dalicia McCowan</Review>< Pics>

My mother-in-law recently passed away, and my family had already made arrangements to have her cremated with another funeral home. Unfortunately the funeral home we chose did not have options for the urn for her remains, so we decided to call Rose Hills to inquire about purchasing an urn.

BIG MISTAKE.

I was very clear over the phone that I was not looking to make any arrangements; I only wanted to browse and purchase an urn. The man I spoke to was named Robert Fox, and initially he seemed very friendly and helpful and told me to come in right away and he would be able to help me out in purchasing an urn

My husband, his brother, and I went immediately and as we arrived, Robert greeted us and lead us to the showroom where the urns were on display. As soon as we entered the room, he turns to us and tells us that we might be better off purchasing an urn on Amazon or Costco because it would be cheaper. Respectfully, we explained that we had already done some browsing, but wanted to see some urns in person, and that if we saw one we liked we would purchase it, regardless of the price.

We did end up finding an urn we really liked, but wanted to look at one other place my husband had seen, and politely told Robert that we would discuss as a family and most likely return the next day to purchase. Once again, Robert suggested we look online because of the price, which we did end up doing, but we couldnt find one similar enough to the one we saw at Rose Hills.

The next day my husband, his aunt, and I returned to Rose Hills ready to purchase the urn. We asked for Robert and told him our intention. He said he would get the paperwork started and disappeared for some time. When he returned, he informed us that they were out of stock and that they would have to order it for us, and that it wouldn't be in until the following Thursday or Friday.

We were okay with this timeframe, and asked if we could pay in advance or put down a security deposit to ensure the urn would be ours. Robert said no, that we should pay when the urn arrives in stock. He took down my number and said he would call us as soon as it arrived in stock. We never received a call back, and it is already past the timeframe he gave us.

At the end of the day, it was obvious that they did not want to sell to us because we did not have my mother-in-law's services with them.

I normally wouldn't mind this, but what bothers me is that instead of telling us this was a policy, they led us on and wasted our time and energy. We are already grieving the loss of someone extremely important, and the lack of professionalism and outright deception from Rose Hills is disgusting.

I do not recommend this place in any sense of the word and would caution anyone to trust them with handling their loved ones final arrangements.< /text>

WARNING! ACHTUNG!  Run, don't walk out of this place.   A Rose Hill (RH)Agent quoted almost 50% higher than Renaker, an independently owned Funeral Home in Buena Park.  Obviously I went with Renaker.

So I called Customer Service @ RH and explained the situation.  1.5 hours later some other salesman was trying to explain how they are the Cadillac of the Funeral Home business; hence the 50% premium increase.  If you want the Cadillac of a cremation service, make sure to call them. They will definitely siphon all your hard earned cash.

So the lesson here is; don't believe the BS.  Be smart and obtain multiple quotes.  My next steps are the BBB & filing a complaint with U.S. AG Xavier Becerra.<//review>
